    "body": "## Background\n\nThe integration tests introduced in #286 each independently define the same\ncontainer setup helpers. `setupTestPostgres`, `runMigrations`, `sanitizeName`,\n`setupTestOpenFGA`, and the Hydra setup logic are copy-pasted across several\ntest files in `pkg/groups`, `pkg/authorization`, `pkg/authentication`, and\n`internal/db`.\n\nThis causes two concrete problems:\n1. **Maintenance drift** — a change to a container image version or a startup\n   flag must be replicated in multiple files; it is easy to miss one.\n2. **Inconsistency** — small divergences already exist (e.g. different\n   container name prefixes, slightly different retry logic).\n\n---\n\n## Proposed solution\n\nCreate `internal/testhelpers` as a regular (non-`_test`) package. Because it\nlives under `internal/`, it cannot leak to external consumers but can be\nimported by any test file in the module. The helpers encode project-specific\ninternals (`internal/db`, embedded migrations, `internal/openfga` model\nwiring), so the visibility restriction is useful.\n\n```\ninternal/\n  testhelpers/\n    containers.go   # per-test container helpers (Postgres, Hydra, OpenFGA)\n    migrations.go   # RunMigrations\n    oauth.go        # Hydra client registration + access-token helpers\n    shared.go       # lazy shared fixtures for container reuse\n```\n\n**Cleanup model:**\n- Per-test helpers register teardown via `t.Cleanup()` — callers never manage\n  cleanup themselves.\n- Shared lazy fixtures live for the test binary lifetime and are closed via\n  `shared.Close()`, which is a no-op if the fixture was never initialized.\n- Per-test resources derived from shared fixtures (e.g. temporary databases)\n  may still use `t.Cleanup()` for their own cleanup.\n- Cleanup failures are logged with `t.Logf`, not `t.Fatalf`, so they don't\n  mask real test failures.\n\n---\n\n## API sketch\n\n### Return types\n\nHelpers return typed structs so callers have everything needed to wire their\ndependencies without doing additional lookups:\n\n```go\ntype PostgresEnv struct {\n    ConnStr string\n}\n\ntype HydraEnv struct {\n    PublicURL string\n    AdminURL  string\n}\n\ntype OpenFGAEnv struct {\n    URL         string\n    APIScheme   string\n    APIHost     string\n    APIToken    string\n    StoreID     string\n    AuthModelID string\n    Client      *openfga.Client\n}\n```\n\n### Container helpers\n\n```go\n// SetupPostgres starts a Postgres container. Teardown is registered on t.\nfunc SetupPostgres(t *testing.T) *PostgresEnv\n\n// RunMigrations runs all goose migrations against connStr.\nfunc RunMigrations(t *testing.T, connStr string)\n\n// SetupHydra starts an Ory Hydra container. Teardown is registered on t.\nfunc SetupHydra(t *testing.T) *HydraEnv\n\n// SetupOpenFGA starts an OpenFGA container, creates a store, and writes the\n// authorization model currently used by the service. Teardown is registered on t.\nfunc SetupOpenFGA(t *testing.T) *OpenFGAEnv\n```\n\n`SetupOpenFGA` does more than start a container — it mirrors what the current\nauthorization integration test does inline: creates a store, writes the model,\nand configures the client with the resulting store ID and model ID. Returning\nonly a URL would force every caller to repeat that wiring.\n\n### OAuth2 helpers\n\n```go\n// CreateHydraClient registers an OAuth2 client_credentials client in Hydra.\n// Best-effort cleanup is registered on t; failures are logged and non-fatal.\n// If the Hydra container is per-test, container teardown is sufficient.\n// ...\n```"
